# Dados não paramétricos com 2 fatores

Para dados com um fator, pode-se usar as 3 alternativas citadas na aula 10. Quando se tem 2 fatores, pode-se analisar cada fator separadamente, mas para testar a interação usa-se outra alternativa.

Conjunto de dados:


::: {.cell hash='Aula18_cache/html/unnamed-chunk-2_b3291a90b73fb841693fde41e4c5cc9f'}

```{.r .cell-code}
fung <- read_excel("dados-diversos.xlsx", "fungicida_vaso")
fung2 <- fung |>
  mutate(inc = inf_seeds/n_seeds*100,
         rank_inc = rank(inc))
rank_anova <- aov(rank_inc ~treat*dose, data = fung2)
summary(rank_anova)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
            Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value  Pr(>F)   
treat        1 220.00  220.00  14.204 0.00168 **
dose         1 105.34  105.34   6.801 0.01904 * 
treat:dose   1  80.34   80.34   5.187 0.03684 * 
Residuals   16 247.82   15.49                   
---
Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
```
:::
:::

Depois usa o emmeans para ver as médias com o rank.


::: {.cell hash='Aula18_cache/html/unnamed-chunk-3_caeadc23542177074165739b58a6ac74'}

```{.r .cell-code}
means_rank <- emmeans(rank_anova, ~treat | dose)
cld(means_rank)
```

# Transformação de variável tipo boxcox


::: {.cell hash='Aula18_cache/html/unnamed-chunk-4_ea8fdcbbc4a4906bf9a49a1613328a68'}

```{.r .cell-code}
library(MASS)
```
:::


Dados:

::: {.cell hash='Aula18_cache/html/unnamed-chunk-5_33930af7ebc918abaacf92b4907b6d64'}

```{.r .cell-code}
insects <- InsectSprays

b <- boxcox(lm(insects$count+0.1 ~1))
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](Aula18_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-5-1.png){width=672}
:::

```{.r .cell-code}
lambda <- b$x[which.max(b$y)]
lambda
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
[1] 0.4242424
```
:::

```{.r .cell-code}
insects$count2 <-(insects$count ^ lambda - 1) / lambda
hist(insects$count)
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](Aula18_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-5-2.png){width=672}
:::
